TY  - JOUR
AU  - Li, Kangli
AU  - van Rijn, Jordan
T1  - Credit Union and Bank Subprime Lending in the Great Recession
PY  - 2024
Y1  - 2024/05/01
DO  - 10.1093/rcfs/cfac020
JO  - The Review of Corporate Finance Studies
JA  - Review of Corporate Finance Studies
VL  - 13
IS  - 2
SP  - 494
EP  - 538
SN  - 2046-9128
AB  - Firm structure affects incentives and performance. We document significant differences in subprime lending between banks and credit unions prior to and during the Great Recession. In 2006, 23.6% of mortgages from commercial banks were subprime versus only 3.6% of mortgages from credit unions. Moreover, banks were more likely to fail, and had higher delinquency and net charge-off ratios immediately following the financial crisis. Our empirical models control for important differences between credit unions and banks including firm-level characteristics, borrower-level characteristics, and state-level economic conditions. We argue that the remaining difference captures the effects of credit unions’ nonprofit and cooperative structure, which encourages them to internalize the utility of their customer-owners. Our findings explain why credit unions often appear more risk averse relative to commercial banks, a result with important research and policy implications. (JEL G12, G31)
Y2  - 4/24/2026
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rcfs/cfac020
ER  - 




